Prologue
"Please!" Queen Eirwen pleaded. "Don't send her away! She's just a child!" The Ice King looked down at his wife from his throne, his royal advisor standing beside him. She had given birth to a daughter. He frowned at this thought.
The little girl looked very much like her mother: pale blue eyes, white hair streaked with blue strands. The Ice King thought a daughter would make him look weak. After all, he had only had sons up to now.
"Your only options are to kill your child or send her back into the wild. It's her punishment for your bad behavior, Eirwen." He spat out her name as if it were poison. He always did.
Frostwell was never always a single kingdom. It had been split into two, the North and the South. In the North, there was a non-magical kingdom. In the South, there was a kingdom filled with fantastical representations of power. Due to the greed of the North, the two kingdoms had torn each other apart in an endless war, until the South proposed a truce.
The South was cornered, and its royal family would have done anything to stop the bloodshed. They proposed that their only princess become queen of the North and bear a son destined to be the future king. Then, the South would have allied with the North to form a single kingdom. The North had accepted, and Princess Eirwen had married Prince Akull.
"Please, my lord, in exchange for my child's life, do with me as you wish—confine me, banish me, or even kill me," pleaded Queen Eirwen, holding her child tightly in her arms.
The Ice King looked down at his wife, hatred in his eyes. Perhaps, perhaps he would have pity for her. The one he had lived with for twenty-two years, who had always taken care of him in his darkest hours, who had given birth to his sons.
"Very well, the child will be able to live in the palace," he began, drawing a sigh of relief from his wife. "However," he added, "you will be executed."
The advisor and Queen Eirwen herself exchanged a horrified glance. She lowered her gaze slowly. "Yes, Your Highness," she said, bowing.
The King of Ice ordered the royal counselor to take the child to one of Eirwen's vacant rooms. Once that was done, he commanded the guards to lead Eirwen to the execution site, where all the townspeople could witness the spectacle.
As the guards escorted her to the site, the inhabitants cried out in outrage upon seeing their only queen, the kindest one, about to be killed. Some wept, others screamed and tried to attack the guards, while others questioned what was happening, but all were filled with indignation.
"Free her!"
"Why are they doing that to him?"
As Eirwen approached the wooden gallows, the most feared person in the kingdom made her entrance. The user of fire. The former queen Eirwen was about to be burned alive. No one deserved such a death, not even criminals. It was the cruelest punishment in Frostfell.
Eirwen was tied to the gallows, and the king began to explain how the queen had betrayed them all. The people of Frostfell refused to believe him and never accepted his words. Then, the user of fire burned the gallows, and a single tear rolled down the cheek of the former queen.
"Survive, Kari." That marked the end of Queen Eirwen's reign.
Silence in the hallways
Tap, tap, tap. These were the only sounds coming from the room farthest to the left in the southern wing of the perpetually frozen palace. The attendants passing by always wondered what was inside that room, frightened of what might be lurking within. The rumors whispered by the servants danced through the corridors. It was believed that the late queen of the Ice King, Eirwen, was in that room, waiting to be freed.
"They couldn't be more wrong," thought Ivory as he walked toward the south wing, while the assistants came and went, murmuring among themselves. They don't have the slightest idea what's in this room.
Of course, these rumors also applied to him, because he was the only person authorized to enter the room.
Toc Toc. "Miss Kari, are you there?" whispered Ivory at the finely decorated door, covered in snowflakes and a crown, the symbol of the royal family.
She wondered if she would invite him in, unlike the other times when he had asked her. I still have bruises from the last time. Ivory giggled at the memory. Kari had thrown a book at his shoulder, but when she realized who it was, she immediately apologized.
A single blow comes from inside, which seemed to mean that she was there, but after all, where else could she have been?
"I can come in?" asked Ivory, remembering the time iel had done so without asking permission.
A loud knock echoed from inside. It seemed to want to say yes. Ivory shivered, not only from the cold, but also from the sound. It was strange for Ivory to hear noise coming from a room supposed to be empty, even though he had entered this room for years.
"I'm here," said Ivory, gently opening the door. The scene inside the room was unusual, according to the standards of normal people, but not unexpected. There were papers everywhere. Books were scattered, the desk was broken, and a multitude of ice statues were scattered around. The room had no windows and almost no light. It was colder than the rest of the palace (and that was saying something). A snowstorm seemed to have been trapped inside.
The girl who was there was curled up on her bed, wrapped in her blanket, reading one of her notebooks. A small lantern illuminated the space.
"Which notebook is it referring to?" Ivory asked as she sat down next to Kari on her bed.
